Crimea and Sudetenland, same battle?
BRUXELLES – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of aggression during peacetime that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is indeed nowadays common to downplay the importance of the "Munich Lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier yielded to Hitler's claims on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
Nevertheless, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea—the second case of the invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the occupation of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008—current democratic leaders might strongly regret their inaction.
Within the Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently under consideration – such as expelling the G8 – could be seen as humorous if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Poutine considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the gravest catastrophe of modern times, an effort by man to resuscitate a fallen Russian Empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin displays.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community has enabled Russia to attract a number of resource-rich countries, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was partitioned in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation forced it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious geostrategic trophy of all — Ukraine — which could well end up in Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explains the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the contrary, strengthened by a suborned and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president is now a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's response be commensurate with the level of adventurism demonstrated by Putin.
Cancellation of summits, proposals for trade agreements, and other participation in as unproductive a forum as the G8 would be insufficient.
Only actions involving the imposition of concrete economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens—who, as we recall, keep re-electing Putin to power—will allow us to hope that the Kremlin will abandon its expansionist path.
What kind of sanctions could it be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian transport, as it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian War.
At that time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it is now clear that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial ships heading to the Russian ports along the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy — as well as on Putin's military ambitions — would prove considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn the argument that Putin used to justify taking Crimea—namely, that he would protect the Russian-speaking ethnic groups living there—back against him by asserting that it itself is protecting its own Turkic ethnic cousins, the Tatars, who clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule due to the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia.
This week, the Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make an emergency U-turn mid-air in order to head to Kiev and provide support to the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows well, is not exactly a soft-hearted leader either, could therefore follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transport – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so that they can return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or in Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia were to attempt to intimidate it.
Secondly, the American president Barack Obama could impose on Russia the same type of financial sanctions that he imposed on Iran around its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed seriously undermined the Iranian economy.
In the same way, denying access to the U.S. financial system to all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialistic course could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in the stability of Eurasia.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was a true tragedy, but for China, it represented the most formidable geostrategic opportunity one could imagine.
In an instant, this empire, which had seized several million hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, was purely and simply wiped out.
Since then, the independent Central Asian states, and Ukraine itself, have become important trade partners of China.
Russia's invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as evidenced by the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held following the war (this regional grouping brings together a number of former Soviet states sharing borders with China and the motherland).
Russia tried to get the OSCE to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organization has however expressed its disagreement.
Or, the Central Asian member states—Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan—could never have risen against the Kremlin without the support of China.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The real test of this Chinese claim to assert itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it support the territorial integrity of Ukraine?
Two other sanction measures are also possible.
Thus, each Russian leader could see their visas denied or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, including those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, particularly for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is leading today will fail.
The cost of inaction could well turn out to be significant.
A number of countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this American promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so under the explicit condition that the United States (together with the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guaranteed its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to re-nuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous formula: "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
"You have chosen disgrace, and you will have war." Today, Obama and other Western leaders are faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose disgrace, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will eventually serve them another war.
